rComments: He has patience and responsibility, especially for new recruits.

I loved taking this class! He has a way of breaking down the material to make it easy to understand and the questions he would ask in class also helped me solidify what I was learning. His assignments and exams are also very fair, as long as you read the powerpoints and answer the wooclap questions you are golden.

I was so scared going into his course because of the ratings on here but this was the most fun class I've had in all of undergrad. Most exam questions are extremely similar to the questions he asks on woolclap so GO TO CLASS!! Pay attention, take good notes and you're golden. No trick questions - if u put in a little effort you will do well.

Please do not listen to what others are saying, I promise he is wonderful. He really cares about his lectures and you can tell by the way he talks about it. The exams and midterm are very fair if you study (and you just really need to read the slides maybe twice) and bonus he repeats some of the participation questions. He is literally so nice.

He taught BCH 4116 (Analytical Biochemistry) this term (which wasn't a selectable option??). The course is very interesting and he even mentions potential jobs and interview questions in the field. All exams and quizzes are open book (notes only) and not monitored. Easy A but not necessarily given. You do need to understand the material to pass.
This guy doesnt even know what hes talking about. He gets lost by his own slides half the time. I was actually looking forward to taking this class but he made it such a pain. Avoid if you can
teacherRatingTags: ['Lots of homework', 'Get ready to read', 'Tough grader']

rComments: Very good professor. There is a language barrier, but he work hard to overcome it by including detailed lecture notes. He is very knowledgeable.
teacherRatingTags: ['Amazing lectures ', 'Get ready to read', 'Beware of pop quizzes']

rComments: Berezovski makes excellent analogies and thoughtful explanations that honestly make the material immensely easier to understand. Yes, the lectures are pretty boring. But show some respect to someone who obviously puts effort into educating students in a language that is not their first. His accent is not hard to understand, just slow to communicate

There's lot of things wrong with this guy. Rumour within Chem department has it that he did some unethical studies and got into problem with supervising students, even undergraduates. Regarding his teaching, would you think a prof who hands out answers during the final exam a good prof? I don't think so. That indicates how bad a teacher he is.
Cut him some slack he's not as bad as everyone is saying here. Dry material and he does his best trying to make it somewhat interesting. Also very approachable, not hard material either.

Long story short: I was in this prof's lab for 2 terms - worst mistake of my life. There are sketchy things done in his lab; and he doesn't care about you at all. Do not remember your name nor yr project. Also treat his students very badly. Peers: stay away from him and save your time by looking for another place for your thesis or summer.
Lectures are super boring, practically useless in fact. Just understand the basics of everything and you're guaranteed 95+ on the exams. The labs are also really boring, but fairly easy.

He is barely able to answer questions of his own materials, also use youtube video or wikipedia materials most of the time. You pass only because he gives you exactly the same thing he gave from prev year ( no effort to teach). Worst, try visiting him in his office once, you may hear him yell at or threat his own grad students. Avoid for life !

He really has no knowledge. The materials he tries to teach in class, honestly, anyone could have done it given the list of subjects needed to cover. All he does is copying and pasting Wikipedia or companies' website materials to show you. Instead of explaining, he would show you Youtube videos. Really is not a scientist, or teacher. Avoid.

Very nice guy. Tries really hard to make the lectures good, but it's really hard to pay attention with his accent. However, his assignments really are there to boast your grade as well as the bonus clicker questions for going to class. Labs were pretty tedious however.
teacherRatingTags: ['EXTRA CREDIT', 'Get ready to read', 'Clear grading criteria']

rComments: Lectures are a bit boring... but when it take him a moment to figure out some of the slides, you kind of empathize. Best part of lectures though are his anecdotes about the pharmaceutical industry. He's a good person to talk to about future plans. He really cares about his students and wants us to do well. Textbook was essential. Labs were great!

He gives hints during the exam when you ask. He walks you through assignments. Although he may not be very clear in the lecture, his expectations are clear because he emphasize important concepts for exams and job interviews! Seriously helpful and wonderful professors! Labs are cruel, but his bonus marks make up for them. Recommended prof.

The worst professor in the faculty of science, possibly the university. Somtimes, he gets confused by his own slides. Switch to the french section, you will probably understand the material better even if you dont speak french.

Learned how to cure insomnia in the class. Hard time speaking English, so not great at explaining. attendance and quizzes were easy marks. The midterm was not bad and the exam was super easy. Does not answer emails because he doesn't care though

One of the worst professor at the University. Terrible at conveying great subject matter, does not test you on what is shown in class, assignments, or dgds, seems not to care to answers private questions after class. Avoid at all costs. (However, can't complain about the amazing labs.)

The worst professor at the University. Takes no time for the students, terrible at conveying subject matter, and does not test you on what is shown in class. Avoid at all costs. It's shocking he's allowed to teach after last year's open book fiasco. It's clear he's making up for it by failing the students this year.

Without the textbook, my mark would have been somewhere around  a 12%. Since the final was open book, and the midterm was take home, I got an A+. The final exam was all definition that could be found in the book, and questions that were nearly identical to those found in the solution manual.

Really easy exams! Exams were open book. He's a smart guy, but doesn't teach that great. Whenever you have a problem you can go and see him and he'll give you bonus points. He explains things great when you ask him. This class was all textbook.

He is the nicest prof ever - gives you bonus points for going to see him. Class was not mandatory, all exams/assignments are open book and all but the midterm were open for a week. He is a really intelligent professor and has a slight difficulty teaching it - but he said the textbook was gold and it was, the class was based off the textbook.

Probably one of the most boring classes I have had to take, especially where the lab portion is worth 40% of your mark (75% of the lab portion is marked on accuracy/precision). He reads off the slides in the lectures and it's hard to pay attention, but he's really nice if you visit him in his office.

I happen to really like this prof. He is very helpful and kind. His lectures are somewhat boring and he sometimes it can be difficult to understand what he's saying, but overall he's done a great job at teaching this course! I'd like to see another professor try and make analytical chem more enjoyable. (can't be done)
Avoid him at all cost. He is very unorganized and rarely posts lecture notes on time.
Don't bother asking questions, he can't answer them. Reads directly from slides which are right out of the textbook.
